# Fluff Date: 2026-03-01 12:28:32
<overview>
<p>The Apostle is an eighty-ton primitive self-propelled artillery vehicle commissioned by the Terran Hegemony in 2321. Designed alongside its lighter companion, the Reaper, the Apostle represented the heavier of two artillery platforms developed to modernize the Hegemony Armed Forces' outdated indirect fire capabilities. Intended to provide long-range heavy fire support at the division level, the vehicle was assigned to battalion-sized artillery formations supporting HAF divisions in the field. As one of the earliest purpose-built self-propelled guns fielded by the Hegemony, the Apostle established a new standard for mobile artillery support that would influence Hegemony military doctrine for generations to come.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Apostle's primary armament is a single Sniper artillery piece mounted in the hull, supported by three tons of ammunition providing thirty rounds of sustained fire. An advanced fire control system guides the weapon, enabling accurate engagement of targets at extreme range, while the ammunition capacity permits the crew to carry multiple munition types as the tactical situation demands. A single front-mounted small laser provides minimal self-defense capability against threats that manage to reach the gun line.</p><p>Powered by an internal combustion engine, the Apostle achieves a cruise speed of thirty-two kilometers per hour with a flank speed of fifty-four. Its generous fuel supply provides an operational range of nearly eleven hundred kilometers, well suited to extended campaigns. Five tons of BAR 6 armor afford basic protection, reflecting the expectation that the vehicle would operate well behind the front lines rather than engage in direct combat. A tractor chassis modification allows the Apostle to tow additional equipment or ammunition trailers, extending its logistical footprint. The large crew of ten, including two officers and six dedicated gunners, ensures smooth operation of the complex artillery system.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Apostle Self-Propelled Artillery served as the primary heavy indirect fire platform for Hegemony Armed Forces division-level operations. Its substantial ammunition capacity and long operational range made it well suited to sustained bombardment campaigns in support of frontline formations. The tractor chassis allowed Apostle batteries to tow additional supplies during extended operations, making the vehicle the centerpiece of HAF heavy artillery battalions.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Apostle and Reaper emerged from a period of urgent military reform following James McKenna's rise to power as the first Director-General of the Terran Hegemony. Field Marshal Mears Coblitz, retained as Commanding General, recognized that the fractured remnants of the old Terran Alliance military desperately needed modernization to prevent the Hegemony from descending into civil war. Among his priorities, the artillery corps had long suffered from neglect, relying on outdated static, towed, and self-propelled pieces inherited from the Alliance era.</p><p>Coblitz personally drafted requirements for two new self-propelled artillery vehicles. The Apostle filled the heavier role, intended for assignment to division-level artillery battalions, while the Reaper served a lighter requirement at the regimental and brigade level. Both vehicles entered service remarkably quickly, debuting in less than two years from initial requirements. The Apostle first saw combat during the later stages of the Campaign of Persuasion, as the Hegemony worked to expand and strengthen its influence across nearby star systems.</p><p>Throughout the late twenty-third century and the decades that followed, the Apostle and Reaper gradually supplanted virtually all of the older Alliance artillery still in service. Both platforms remained in frontline use for more than a century before advancing technology rendered them obsolete. The Apostle received its formal obsolescence designation in 2485, replaced by newer designs incorporating standard rather than primitive technology. Despite this, a handful of examples survived into the thirty-first century. By the dawn of the Dark Age, at least a few Apostles remained as ceremonial vehicles stationed on Terra and New Earth.</p>
</history>

